Because in the start rule the left‑hand component comes first,

    S → NT12 NT28

all tokens before the single token produced by NT28 must be generated by NT12.

NT12 can begin in only five ways:

1. NT12 → 't19' | 't18' | 't23' | 't11'           (first token fixed)
2. NT12 → NT3  NT23                               (first token from NT3)
3. NT12 → NT41 NT32                               (first token from NT41)
4. NT12 → NT39 NT39                               (first token from the first NT39)
5. NT12 → NT19 NT48                               (first token from NT19)

Examining every non‑terminal that can appear first in these rules:

• NT3 can yield t9, t6, or t25.
• NT41 can yield t8, t15, or start with NT14 (which can yield t19, t7, t13, t25, t3).
• NT39 can yield t7, t5, t1, or start with NT0/NT11/NT21, none of which can start with t24.
• NT19 can yield t22, t5, t25, t11, t20, t15, t9, t8, t3, t2.
• The four direct lexical alternatives are t19, t18, t23, t11.

In no case can the very first token produced by NT12 be t24.

Since the given string begins with t24, NT12 cannot generate it; consequently S cannot generate it either.

Therefore the string is not in the language of the grammar.

No

The first symbol of the string is ‘t10’.  
In the grammar a terminal ‘t10’ can be produced only by the three
pre‑terminals  

 NT30 → ‘t10’  NT34 → ‘t10’  NT46 → ‘t10’.

Hence the left‑most derivation of any sentence that begins with ‘t10’
must start with one of these three non‑terminals.

1. If the derivation starts with NT30, the only binary rule that can have
NT30 as its left child is

 NT1 → NT30 NT42.

Thus the second token must be the first token generated by NT42.
NT42, however, can begin only with

 t16   or  t25 / t3 / t14 / t23 / t17   or one of t15 t19 t9 t6 t13.

In no case can NT42 begin with ‘t2’.  
Therefore NT30 cannot yield the prefix “t10 t2”.

2. If the derivation starts with NT46, the only binary rule that can
place NT46 first is

 NT15 → NT46 NT14.

Hence the second token is the first token produced by NT14.
NT14 can start with only  

 t19, t7, t13, t25, t3, t8, t10, t9, t4, t21, t23 …  

but never with ‘t2’.  
So the sequence “t10 t2” cannot come from NT46 either.

3. If the derivation starts with NT34, the only rule featuring NT34 in
first position is

 NT4 → NT34 NT44.

Consequently the second token is the first token delivered by NT44.
NT44 can begin with  

 t18, t23, t25, t3, t15, t9, t8, t5, t22 …

and again ‘t2’ is impossible.

Thus no derivation in the grammar can produce the prefix
“t10 t2”.  Because the given string necessarily starts with that
prefix, it is not in the language generated by the grammar.

No
